tinue without model information. If the hint file exists but cannot be read due to a permissions issue, the user gets no indication that model tracking is broken.\n\n**Hidden Errors:**\n- `os.ReadFile` returning `os.ErrPermission` (file permission denied) -- silently treated as \"no hint\"\n- `os.ReadFile` returning I/O errors (disk failure, NFS timeout) -- silently treated as \"no hint\"\n- `getSessionStateDir` failing due to broken git state (not in a git repo, corrupted .git) -- silently treated as \"no hint\"\n- `validation.ValidateSessionID` catching a path traversal attempt -- silently swallowed with no logging\n\n**User Impact:** If the hint file exists but cannot be read, the model name is silently lost. The user sees checkpoints without model attribution and has no way to know why. Debugging this 6 months from now would require guessing that `LoadModelHint` might be the culprit.\n\n**Recommendation:** Log non-`os.ErrNotExist` errors at Warn level using the project's `logging` package. The function signature returning a plain string is fine for the callers, but the errors should be observable.\n\n**Example of corrected code:**\n\n```go\nfunc LoadModelHint(ctx context.Context, sessionID string) string {\n\tif err := validation.ValidateSessionID(sessionID); err != nil {\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\n\tstateDir, err := getSessionStateDir(ctx)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlogging.Warn(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \"session\"), \"failed to resolve state dir for model hint\",\n\t\t\tslog.String(\"session_id\", sessionID),\n\t\t\tslog.Any(\"error\", err))\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\n\thintPath := filepath.Join(stateDir, sessionID+\".model\")\n\tdata, err := os.ReadFile(hintPath)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tif !os.IsNotExist(err) {\n\t\t\tlogging.Warn(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \"session\"), \"failed to read model hint file\",\n\t\t\t\tslog.String(\"path\", hintPath),\n\t\t\t\tslog.Any(\"error\", err))\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn \"\"\n\t}\n\treturn string(data)\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 2: `handleLifecycleModelUpdate` silently swallows `LoadSessionState` errors\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`, lines 144-152\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Issue Description:**\nThe condition `if state, err := strategy.LoadSessionState(ctx, event.SessionID); err == nil && state != nil` silently falls through to the hint-file path when `LoadSessionState` returns an error. The error from `LoadSessionState` (which could be a corrupted state file, permission issue, or broken git repo) is completely discarded. The function then writes a hint file as if the state simply does not exist yet.\n\nThis is a masked error -- if the session state file IS corrupt, the function silently falls back to writing a hint file, which could lead to inconsistency: the corrupt state file persists while a hint file is also created alongside it. On the next `TurnStart`, `LoadSessionState` may fail again, the hint file gets read, but the model never makes it into the state because saving into a corrupt state continues to fail.\n\n**Hidden Errors:**\n- `LoadSessionState` returning a JSON unmarshal error (corrupt `.json` file) -- silently falls through to hint file\n- `LoadSessionState` returning a state store creation error -- silently falls through\n- Any transient I/O error -- treated the same as \"state does not exist\"\n\n**User Impact:** Users with corrupted session state files will see model information silently lost on every `ModelUpdate` event. The hint file gets written, but the model may never reach the session state.\n\n**Recommendation:** Log the error from `LoadSessionState` at Debug or Warn level before falling through to the hint-file path. This makes the fallback behavior observable.\n\n**Example of corrected code:**\n\n```go\n// Prefer writing directly to session state when it exists\nstate, loadErr := strategy.LoadSessionState(ctx, event.SessionID)\nif loadErr != nil {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"could not load session state for model update, using hint file\",\n        slog.String(\"error\", loadErr.Error()))\n}\nif loadErr == nil && state != nil {\n    state.ModelName = event.Model\n    if saveErr := strategy.SaveSessionState(ctx, state); saveErr != nil {\n        logging.Warn(logCtx, \"failed to update session state with model\",\n            slog.String(\"error\", saveErr.Error()))\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 3: `handleLifecycleModelUpdate` silently returns nil for empty SessionID or Model\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`, lines 140-142\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:**\nWhen `event.SessionID == \"\"` or `event.Model == \"\"`, the function returns `nil` (success) after logging the event with those empty values. This is a silent no-op. Compare with `handleLifecycleSessionStart` (line 72-73) which returns an error when `SessionID` is empty: `return fmt.Errorf(\"no session_id in %s event\", event.Type)`.\n\nThe inconsistency is notable: for `SessionStart` a missing `SessionID` is a hard error, but for `ModelUpdate` it is silently ignored. The `parseBeforeModel` function already guards against empty model (line 200-201 of `lifecycle.go` in geminicli), but `handleLifecycleModelUpdate` can still be called with empty values if a different agent implementation produces a `ModelUpdate` event with empty fields.\n\n**User Impact:** If a new agent implementation sends a `ModelUpdate` event with an empty `SessionID`, the error is silently swallowed with no logging -- making it invisible during integration development.\n\n**Recommendation:** At minimum, log at Debug level when the early return fires. Consider whether an empty `SessionID` on a `ModelUpdate` should be a validation error (consistent with other handlers).\n\n**Example of corrected code:**\n\n```go\nif event.SessionID == \"\" || event.Model == \"\" {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"skipping model-update: missing session_id or model\",\n        slog.String(\"session_id\", event.SessionID),\n        slog.String(\"model\", event.Model))\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 4: `StateStore.Clear` silently discards hint file removal errors\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go`, line 350\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:**\nThe line `_ = os.Remove(hintFile)` explicitly discards ALL errors from removing the hint file, including permission errors. The comment says \"Best-effort cleanup\" which is understandable -- the state file removal is the primary operation. However, this is inconsistent with the `ClearSessionState` function in the strategy layer (`session_state.go` lines 281-284) which logs a warning when hint file removal fails for non-`NotExist` errors.\n\nThe two `Clear` implementations (`session/state.go:Clear` and `strategy/session_state.go:ClearSessionState`) are called from different code paths, meaning hint file cleanup errors are sometimes logged and sometimes completely swallowed, depending on which path invokes the cleanup.\n\n**Hidden Errors:**\n- `os.Remove` returning `os.ErrPermission` -- silently ignored\n- Orphaned `.model` files accumulating if removal consistently fails\n\n**User Impact:** Hint files could accumulate over time if there is a persistent permission issue in the state directory. No diagnostics would surface this.\n\n**Recommendation:** Log non-`NotExist` errors at Debug or Warn level, consistent with the strategy-layer implementation.\n\n**Example of corrected code:**\n\n```go\nhintFile := filepath.Join(s.stateDir, sessionID+\".model\")\nif err := os.Remove(hintFile); err != nil && !os.IsNotExist(err) {\n    logCtx := logging.WithComponent(ctx, \"session\")\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"failed to remove model hint file during clear\",\n        slog.String(\"path\", hintFile),\n        slog.Any(\"error\", err))\n}\n```\n\nNote: This requires the `session/state.go` `Clear` method to actually use the `ctx` parameter (currently assigned to `_`). That is a minor refactor worth doing.\n\n---\n\n## Issue 5: `ExtractModelFromTranscript` uses `slog.Warn` instead of project logging\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/factoryaidroid/transcript.go`, lines 308-310\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:**\nThe newly added warning for corrupt settings files uses `slog.Warn` directly from the standard library, bypassing the project's `logging` package (`logging.Warn`). The CLAUDE.md explicitly states: \"Internal/debug logging: Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error(ctx, msg, attrs...)` from `cmd/entire/cli/logging/`.\" Using `slog` directly means this warning goes to the default slog handler (likely stderr or nowhere) rather than the project's structured log files in `.entire/logs/`.\n\nAdditionally, the function does not accept a `context.Context` parameter, so it cannot use the project's logging infrastructure which requires context for component tagging and session correlation. This is a pre-existing limitation, but the PR is the right time to address it since it is actively modifying this code path.\n\n**User Impact:** The warning about corrupt settings files will NOT appear in `.entire/logs/` where operators look for diagnostic information. It goes to stderr (or nowhere) instead, making it invisible in the standard debugging workflow.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either pass `context.Context` into `ExtractModelFromTranscript` and use `logging.Warn`, or acknowledge this as a known limitation with a code comment. At minimum, the `slog.Warn` call should be documented as intentionally bypassing the project logger.\n\n---\n\n## Issue 6: `StoreModelHint` does not validate or sanitize the model string\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/session_state.go`, lines 218-238\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:**\nThe `model` parameter is written directly to a file without any length check or content validation. While the `sessionID` is validated against path traversal, the model string could be arbitrarily long or contain unexpected content. A malicious or buggy agent could send a multi-megabyte model string, which would be written to disk without question.\n\nFurthermore, `LoadModelHint` reads the file back and returns it as `string(data)` without any trimming or validation. If the file happens to contain trailing whitespace or newlines (from a future bug or manual edit), those would be silently propagated into `event.Model` and then into `state.ModelName`.\n\n**Hidden Errors:** Not a hidden error per se, but a missing defensive check that could lead to subtle bugs (model name containing whitespace, unexpected file sizes).\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a basic length check on the model string and trim whitespace on read.\n\n```go\n// In StoreModelHint:\nif len(model) > 256 {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"model name too long: %d characters\", len(model))\n}\n\n// In LoadModelHint:\nreturn strings.TrimSpace(string(data))\n```\n\n---\n\n## Positive Observations\n\nSeveral aspects of the error handling in this PR are well done:\n\n1. **`StoreModelHint` validates the session ID** against path traversal before constructing file paths (line 219). This is good security practice.\n\n2. **`ClearSessionState` in the strategy layer** (`session_state.go` lines 281-284) correctly logs hint file removal failures at Warn level with path and error context, distinguishing `NotExist` from real errors. This is the right pattern.\n\n3. **The doc comment on `StoreModelHint`** (lines 199-217) thoroughly explains the architectural rationale for the hint file pattern, making the design decision clear for future maintainers.\n\n4. **`handleLifecycleModelUpdate` correctly logs the incoming event** with session_id and model before any processing (lines 135-138).\n\n5. **Tests cover the cleanup paths** including orphaned hint files (`TestStateStore_Clear_RemovesHintFileWithoutStateFile`) and corrupt settings files (`TestExtractModelFromTranscript_CorruptSettingsFile`).\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Findings\n\n| # | Location | Severity | Issue |\n|---|----------|----------|-------|\n| 1 | `strategy/session_state.go:243-258` | HIGH | `LoadModelHint` silently swallows ALL errors including permissions/I/O |\n| 2 | `lifecycle.go:144-152` | HIGH | `handleLifecycleModelUpdate` discards `LoadSessionState` errors |\n| 3 | `lifecycle.go:140-142` | MEDIUM | Silent no-op return for empty SessionID/Model without logging |\n| 4 | `session/state.go:350` | MEDIUM | `StateStore.Clear` discards hint removal errors inconsistently |\n| 5 | `factoryaidroid/transcript.go:308-310` | MEDIUM | Uses `slog.Warn` instead of project `logging` package |\n| 6 | `strategy/session_state.go:218-238` | MEDIUM | No length/content validation on model string |\n\nIssues 1 and 2 are the most impactful. `LoadModelHint` is called on every `TurnStart` and `TurnEnd` for sessions where the model was not directly provided on the hook. If these calls fail silently, model attribution is lost with zero diagnostic trail. Issue 2 creates a scenario where a corrupted state file causes permanent model information loss through an invisible fallback.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>91724</total_tokens><tool_uses>12</tool_uses><duration_ms>113909</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-1/tasks/ab98258f94467f301.output\n\n---\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a144e4271e66df9c0</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>REDACTED</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review test coverage\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good -- the type consolidation (merging `sessionStartRaw` into `sessionInfoRaw` with `Model` as `omitempty`) is safe because `sessionInfoRaw` is now used for all three hooks (SessionStart, TurnEnd, SessionEnd), and the `Model` field simply won't be populated for SessionEnd/Stop hooks.\n\nNow I have a comprehensive pict